The Telegraph - Calcutta
 Friday, November 29, 2002  Calcutta Column
 
	The motorised country boats that ply between Belur Math  and Dakshineswar, take on more people than is their capacity.  Neither are they well-maintained, leading to cracks on  the sides. There is a high risk of the boats capsizing,  especially during the rains or high tide. The authorities  should look into the condition of the boats. Moreover,  to promote tourism at the two holy sites, the state can  introduce ferry services across the river. Jyoti Baksi,  Heysham Row				 																																									In these days of acute housing crisis, getting a foothold in Calcutta is difficult, especially for students from the districts. Earlier, these students would stay in college hostels or in accomodations provided by charitable institutes. 				 																																									Economic compulsions have forced these institutions to abandon the facilities. Premier colleges too are discontinuing hostel facilities as the hostels are occupied by illegal occupants. Where will students from outside put up?				 																																									Debaprasad Mukherjee,				 																																									Nayapatty Road.
